        <bioghist id="ref16">
            <head>Biographical/Historical note</head>
            <p>George Shally enlisted in the United States Army in 1944 while he was in college in Berkeley, CA. He joined because he wanted to fight against the Nazi regime of Germany, and in the army he knew he would be able to serve in the infantry. Shally went to basic training in Florida, where they had to march 25 miles a day during the summer. He then transferred to California, where his division practiced invasions on a small island. When his infantry division shipped to the European theater, they began marching in France, and then marched all the way to Austria. In the infantry, Shally served as rifleman and first scout. He describes the conditions he faced when fighting in the Battle of the Bulge and other combat situations. After the war was declared over in Europe, he was transferred to the Pacific, where his division was going to take part in the invasion of Japan; however, the war was over before he could be transferred. He was sent to Luzon (Philippines) instead, where he rounded up Japanese soldiers who were unaware that the war had ended.. Shally was discharged in May of 1946, and when he returned home and finished college with the GI Bill.</p>
        </bioghist>
